    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-05-31T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-05-31T05:00:00-05:00" n="521"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760F.62/370: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-31T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 31, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 1:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>851. There has been considerable comment in the French press concerning Secretary
                    Hull’s statement with regard to Central Europe and the Briand–Kellogg Pact.<note
                        n="65" xml:id="d521fn65">Statement of May 28, <ref target="#pg_520">p.
                            520</ref>.</note> This comment covered the following points: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>The Secretary purposely chose the time for this declaration due to the
                            situation in Central Europe on the eve of the second elections in
                            Czechoslovakia;</item>
                        <pb facs="0532" n="524" xml:id="pg_524"/>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>The declaration was considered as a support of the efforts of England
                            and France towards a peaceful solution of the Czechoslovak
                            question;</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>It was of extreme importance since it was a public declaration
                            indicating the interest of the United States in the maintenance of peace
                            in Central Europe.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
